        "### Bootstrap Interpretation\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Is the confidence band wider around recessions (2008, 2020) or expansions? Why?\n",
        "2. Why do we use **block** bootstrap instead of standard i.i.d. bootstrap? What would go wrong if we shuffled residuals independently?\n",
        "3. How does the choice of `block_size=8` affect the results? What would happen with `block_size=1` (equivalent to i.i.d. bootstrap) or `block_size=20`?"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "0PMxNldsJkl_"
      },
      "source": [
        "*Your answers here:*\n",
        "\n",
        "1. The bands are wider around recessions (2008, 2020) because the residuals are larger during those periods, STL can't absorb sudden economic shocks. When the bootstrap resamples those large-residual blocks it creates more variation in the reconstructed series, so the trend estimates are more spread out. Basically more volatility = more trend uncertainty.\n",
        "2. We use block bootstrap because time series residuals are autocorrelated — today's residual is correlated with yesterday's. Regular i.i.d. bootstrap shuffles them randomly which destroys that dependence and produces artificially choppy residuals that don't look like the original series. Block bootstrap keeps contiguous chunks together so the autocorrelation structure is preserved.\n",
        "3. block_size=1 is the same as i.i.d. bootstrap — it destroys all autocorrelation and produces bands that are too narrow because the resampled series are less smooth than the original. block_size=20 preserves more dependence but you have fewer blocks to sample from so the bootstrap loses diversity. block_size=8 (2 years) is a good middle ground for quarterly data because it roughly spans a business cycle phase."
      ]
